<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH / A SPECIAL REPORT: SWIMMING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Erik Hamilton 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 ALL WET: It's the swimming season, and Southern California will have its share 
of big meets. Janet Evans, graduate of El Dorado High in Placentia and two-time 
Olympian, will be busy; included in her itinerary will be the Swim Meet of 
Champions Thursday through Sunday at Marguerite Aquatics Complex in Mission 
Viejo. Says Mission Viejo Nadadores Coach Bill Rose: "If you want to see some 
of the top swimmers in the country, this is the meet to come to." . . . Several 
other meets, including the Janet Evans Invitational July 21-24 at USC, will 
lead to the world championships in September in Rome. 
</P>
<P>
 MAKING A SPLASH: Swimming isn't a glamour sport, but Aliso Viejo's Bjorn 
Zikarsky says it has helped his acting career. The 6-foot-10 Zikarsky, who 
competed for West Germany in the 1988 Olympics and trains with the Irvine 
Novaquatics Swim Club with an eye on the 1996 Games, said the sport got him 
into USC and has been a factor in landing roles. "It's given me the full ride," 
he says. His latest gig: a commercial with NBA star Shaquille O'Neal. 
</P>
<P>
 GUPPIES: Top swimmers often seem as if they were born that way, but Johnny 
Johnson (above, with 3-year-old Scott Thomsen) says no. Johnson, co-owner of 
Blue Buoy Swim School in Tustin and Santa Ana, has seen some of the best -- 
including Olympians -- since going to work there in 1967. . . . "I remember 
some of them screaming, crying for Mommy, when they got in the water," he says. 
Most parents just want to make children pool-safe, he says, but after they 
start learning the strokes, "things start opening up." 
</P>
<P>
 JUNK FOOD: Before Sandy Zubrin, a senior-to-be at Corona del Mar High, left 
for the China Open Diving Invitational last month, she was warned about the 
food. But she still wasn't prepared for the bat wings and dog served her first 
day there. "Every day was a surprise, and she really dreaded going down to 
breakfast," said her mother, Bonnie. . . . Thanks to peanut butter and 
crackers, Sandy survived until she found some food she was used to. Zubrin will 
compete July 1-4 in the Southern California Diving Invitational at Marguerite 
Aquatics Complex. Erik Hamilton 
</P>
</TEXT>
